\emph default
 of a homomorphism was introduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By this time, people had got a bit of a taste for the purely abstract study
 of group theory: it excited them that they could think about a group such
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{5}$
\end_inset

 without saying whether its elements were rotations of a pentagon or integers
 mod 5 or something else entirely.
 So people started studying groups 
\emph on
for their own sake
\emph default
.
 And one of the first questions they asked was this: we know that kernels
 of homomorphisms are subgroups, but what about the converse? That is, is
 every subgroup the kernel of some homomorphism?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem turned out not to be very interesting, since there were easy
 counterexamples.
 For example, if you take the permutation group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 and take the subgroup that consists of the identity and the transposition
 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

, then that is not the kernel of any homomorphism.
 The original proof of this fact went something like this.
 Suppose we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 goes to the identity.
 We can use that to deduce that, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

 also goes to the identity.
 We do this by ``using 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 to do 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

'' as follows.
 We first find a permutation that switches 1 and 3---the obvious one being
 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)$
\end_inset

.
 We then switch 1 and 3, perform the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 and finally switch 1 and 3 back again.
 More formally, we calculate the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)(12)(13)$
\end_inset

, and we note that because we began and ended by swapping 1 and 3 round,
 this new permutation does to 3 what the old one did to 1 and vice versa.
 So the resulting permutation is 
\begin_inset Formula $(32)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

---and 
\begin_inset Formula $(32)$
\end_inset

 is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does that prove? Well, if we now think about what 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(23)$
\end_inset

 must be, it is the result of multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(12)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(12)$
\end_inset

 is the identity and 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)$
\end_inset

 is its own inverse, we end up just doing 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

 and inverting it again.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

 also belongs to the kernel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was soon realized that this basic trick could be used to generate lots
 of counterexamples.
 All you had to do was find a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, an element 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 was not in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 And that was easy to do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Soon this observation was turned into a formal definition.
 A subgroup H was said to be 
\emph on
closed under conjugation
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 And now the original question was modified in an obvious way.
 The argument used to generate counterexamples could be encapsulated in
 the following statement: the kernel of a homomorphism must always be closed
 under conjugation.
 (Proof: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(h)=e$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(ghg^{-1})=\phi(g)\phi(h)\phi(g^{-1})=\phi(g)\phi(g^{-1})=\phi(e)=e.$
\end_inset

) So what about the converse? Is every subgroup that is closed under conjugation
 the kernel of some homomorphism?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This question is an example of a phenomenon that occurs frequently in mathematic
s.
 You find a very simple 
\emph on
necessary
\emph default
 condition for something to be the case.
 (In this example, being closed under conjugation is a necessary condition
 for a subgroup to be the kernel of a homomorphism.) You then attempt to
 show that that condition is 
\emph on
sufficient
\emph default
.
 It’s always a pleasant surprise when you manage, since it is far from obvious
 in advance that the conditions you have identified are the only obstacles
 to getting what you want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, for instance, it isn’t obvious at all that just because a subgroup
 satisfies a condition that it clearly has to satisfy, it must be the kernel
 of some homomorphism.
 Where’s that homomorphism going to come from? There isn’t another group
 around, let alone a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to that group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem was found quite hard at the time, though the technique used
 to solve it has since become standard.
 The original thought process that led to a solution went something like
 this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
If you are trying to find something complicated but have no idea where to
 start, then pretend you’ve found what you are looking for and see what
 you can say about it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So let’s pretend we have a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to some group 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and that the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 What can we say about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well, one thing we know immediately is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(h)=e$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, since that was our initial assumption.
 What can we do with that information? One thing it tells us is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(gh)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(hg)$
\end_inset

.
 So that tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 whenever we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=hg$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=gh$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let’s explore that a little more.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Can we say precisely for which elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in G$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

? We’ve shown that it must when 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=hg$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that, we used the fact that every 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 But we also know the converse: that every element of the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}g'\in H$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g^{-1}g')=\phi(g^{-1})\phi(g')=\phi(g)^{-1}\phi(g)=e$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we have just established, using only the information that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}g'\in H$
\end_inset

, which is the same as saying that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in gH$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is constant on the left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 but takes different values on different left cosets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But I could have argued slightly differently.
 I could have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g'g^{-1})=e$
\end_inset

, and therefore concluded that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g'g^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in Hg$
\end_inset

.
 This would have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is constant on the right cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, and that it takes different values on different right cosets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two observations are incompatible with each other unless every left
 coset is a right coset and vice versa.
 So we’d better check that.
 What right coset of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 might be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

? Well, it had better contain 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg$
\end_inset

 is a pretty obvious choice.
 Does 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg$
\end_inset

? The answer is yes if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

.
 But H is closed under conjugation, so we’re OK.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where have we got to now? We have shown that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to a group 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and if the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 must be constant on the cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 — and we have also shown that I’m allowed to say ``cosets'' because the
 left and right cosets coincide.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 must take different values on different cosets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is that all we can say? Very much not.
 If we have an ounce of mathematical curiosity, then sooner or later we
 will start to wonder whether we can say anything about how the values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on different cosets are related to each other.
 If we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}H$
\end_inset

 and the value 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}H$
\end_inset

, can we deduce anything from that? Well, the main thing we know about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is that it is a homomorphism, so let’s try to use that fact.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1},h_{2}\in H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g_{1}h_{1})=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g_{2}h_{2})=b$
\end_inset

, so 
