\begin_layout Chapter
Third Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that image of subgroup is subgroup of image.
 What about normal subgroups? Is image of normal subgroup normal in image
 ? Or Inverse image of normal is normal in G?.
 After we answer these questions, you should wonder is there any relation
 between the quotient in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and the quotient in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a normal subgroup of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G/H\simeq\frac{G/N}{H/N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Define the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon G/N\to G/H$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(gN\right)=gH.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is well defined because 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}N=g_{2}N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}^{-1}g_{2}\in N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\subset H$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}H=g_{2}H$
\end_inset

 .
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism onto 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 .
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 is normal and by the first isomorphism theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(G/N\right)=G/H\simeq\frac{G/N}{H/N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Cayley Tables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with ``counting Cayley tables'' is that they mostly only come
 up at the beginning of one's study of group theory, whereas it takes some
 group-theoretic sophistication to understand how and what to count, especially
 when two Cayley tables are to be regarded as distinct.
 In order to avoid a lot of tables which are permutations of each other,
 let's adopt the convention that whenever a product of two group elements
 is an element that hasn't yet appeared above and to the left of it in the
 table, one should name the new element with the next available letter in
 the alphabet or the identity .
 We illustrate this with the classification of all groups of order 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is one possibility:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline +_{\mathbb{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{Z}}}_{2}\times\mathbb{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{Z}}}_{2}} & e & a & b & c\\
\hline e & e & a & b & c\\
\hline a & a & e & c & b\\
\hline b & b & c & e & a\\
\hline c & c & b & a & e
\\\hline \end{array}
\]

\end_inset

Let us go through the steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The first row is clear since 
\begin_inset Formula $e\circ x=x$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the second row we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ a=e$
\end_inset

 sinc 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 has not appeared to the left or above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ b$
\end_inset

 has to be 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ c=b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the third row 
\begin_inset Formula $b\circ b=e$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally the last row is uniquely determined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an example of the so called 
\emph on
Klein 4 group
\emph default
 in which every element is of order 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now suppose we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ a=b$
\end_inset

 (the next available letter) in step 2 above.
 Then we shall get the following table:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline +_{4} & e & a & b & c\\
\hline e & e & a & b & c\\
\hline a & a & b & c & e\\
\hline b & b & c & e & a\\
\hline c & c & e & a & b
\\\hline \end{array}
\]

\end_inset

This is the abelian group of the integers modulo 4: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{Z}}}/(4),+_{4})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

